    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="NA26-kiḷavi">itu talaivi pirivuṇarntu vēṟupaṭṭamai collit tōḻi celavaḻuṅkuvittatu.</p>
        <p xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante prevents [HIS] going, speaking of HER having changed after understanding that [HE] would separate.</p>
      </div>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="NA26">
<l>            nōkō yāṉē nekiḻntaṉa vaḷaiyē</l>
<l>            cevvi cērnta puḷḷi veḷḷarai</l>
<l>            viṇṭup puraiyum puṇarnilai neṭuṅkūṭṭup</l>
<l>            piṇṭa nelliṉ ṟāymaṉai yoḻiyac</l>
<l>            cuṭarmuḻu teṟippat tiraṅkic ceḻuṅkāy </l>
<l>            muṭamutir palavi ṉatta nummoṭu</l>
<l>            keṭutuṇai yākiya tavaṟō vaiyeyiṟṟup</l>
<l>            poṉpotin taṉṉa cuṇaṅki</l>
<lg type="alternate"><l>ṉiruñcū ḻōtip peruntō ḷāṭkē.</l>
    <l>miṉṉī rōtip paṇaiperun tōḷē</l></lg>

</lg>
        <lg xml:lang="en">
<l>Ah, I ache. They have become loose, [my] bangles,</l>
<l>– for her of big shoulders, with dark hair all around,</l>
<l rend="indent2">with beauty spots like piled gold, with sharp teeth.</l>
<l>[Would it be] a mistake [for her]<note place="foot">Perhaps the second possibility to connect the dative <term xml:lang="ta">tōḷāṭkē</term> at the end of the poem is <term xml:lang="ta">tavaṟō</term>.</note> to become the companion</l>
<l>to get lost</l>
<l rend="indent2">with you on the road of jack-fruit trees,</l>
<l rend="indent2">where abundant unripe fruits ripen crookedly,</l>
<l rend="indent2">having dried up as the [sun's] glow shines on all(?)<note place="foot">What is the significance of <term xml:lang="ta">muḻutu</term> here?</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent">while [her] mother's house with [its] paddy in balls<note place="foot">Is <term xml:lang="ta">piṇṭam</term> here Skt. piṇṭa-? Does it just refer to a special preparation of the paddy? In any case it signifies a rich house which SHE is willing to leave for HIM.</note> stays behind,</l>
<l rend="indent">[after] being together for long in a state of union<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">puṇar nilai neṭuṅ kūṭṭu</term>: this phrase can refer to THEIR being together (and quite explicitly to the erotic nature of their connection), either already before their elopement or also after, or to HER having stayed at home up to now with the mother.</note>,</l>
<l rend="indent3">which resembles a mountain with dotted white base</l>
<l rend="indent4">joined by red(?)<note place="foot">The comparison as such is already enigmatic, if it is not simply meant to be a hyperbolic metaphor of the KT3 type: a connection as solid/big as a mountain. More enigmatic are the details given in line 2: what is the <term xml:lang="ta">veḷ arai</term> of a mountain, and what can be said by <term xml:lang="ta">cevvi cērnta puḷḷi</term> (if the text is correct here at all)? Th.A. suggests to read a reference to the sky at dusk here: "which resembles the air whose white half has marks tinged with red".</note>?</l>
            </lg>
         </div>
